{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473593"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:10:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:10:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2525"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2525"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.04,0.75,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2525"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50814"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2525"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2525"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36055"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3711"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18209"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50814"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old girl is brought by her parent to see her general practitioner as she suffers from recurrent nosebleeds. This has been recurring over the past few years, however they self-resolve without any hospitalisation required. She has also had heavy menstrual bleeding, with menstrual periods lasting six days and on the heaviest days she requires seven pads. This has led to her missing up to five days of school per month. She underwent dental extraction five years ago which was complicated by heavy post-operative bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations are shown below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 100 g/L (115-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular volume: 69 fL (76-86)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 10 g/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 285 g/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProthrombin time (PT): 12 seconds (11-13)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInternational normalised ratio (INR): 1.0 (0.9 to 1.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActivated partial thromboplastin time (APTT): 37 seconds (25-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haemophilia A","Haemophilia B","von Willebrand disease","Factor V Leiden","Bernard-Soulier syndrome"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a young girl who presents with mucocutaneous bleeding (e.g., heavy menstrual bleeding, nosebleeds). These suggest \u003Cstrong\u003Evon Willebrand disease\u003C/strong\u003E (vWD), the most common inherited bleeding disorder affecting approximately 1% of the general population. Most cases show an autosomal dominant inheritance pattern. It can be associated with thrombocytopenia and factor VIII deficiency, sometimes manifesting with an increased activated partial thromboplastin time (aPTT).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn vWD, there is a quantitative or qualitative defect of the von Willebrand factor (vWF), which facilitates platelet adhesion and carries Factor VIII to prevent it from being degraded. Hence, mucocutaneous bleeding is common in individuals with vWD. This can result in iron deficiency, a common cause of microcytic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilia A\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilia B\u003C/strong\u003E are X-linked recessive disorders resulting in mutation in factor VIII and IX, respectively. Hence males are more commonly affected. They typically present with deep tissue bleeding (e.g., hemarthroses) rather than mucocutaneous bleeding. Table 1 summarises the key differences between vWD and haemophilia A or B.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFactor V, a coagulation factor, is degraded by activated protein C. In \u003Cstrong\u003EFactor V Leiden\u003C/strong\u003E, a gene mutation results in the inability for this to to occur. Hence individuals with homozygous Factor V Leiden mutation are at increased risk of venous thromboembolism, not bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBernard-Soulier syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare autosomal recessive disorder characterised by a defect in platelet aggregation due to a defect in Glycoprotein Ib, leading to mucocutaneous bleeding. Thrombocytopenia is commonly present. It is also much rarer than vWD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETable 1. Comparison between von Willebrand disease and haemophilia A or B\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Von Willebrand disease is the most common inherited bleeding disorder, affecting approximately 1% of the general population","In vWD, there is a quantitative or qualitative defect of the von Willebrand factor (vWF)","Mucocutaneous bleeding is common in vWD, in contrast to deep tissue bleeding more commonly seen in haemophilia."],"references":["Castaman G, Goodeve A, Eikenboom J. Principles of care for the diagnosis and treatment of von Willebrand Disease. Haematologica. 2013; 98(5): 667-674.","Favaloro EJ, Pasalic L, Curnow J. Diagnosis and management of von Willebrand disease in Australia. 2018 [Internet]. 2018;3. Available from: https://aob.amegroups.org/article/view/4450","James PD, Connell NT, Ameer B, Di Paola J, Eikenboom J, Giraud N, et al. ASH ISTH NHF WFH 2021 guidelines on the diagnosis of von Willebrand disease. Blood Advances. 2021 Jan 12;5(1):280\u2013300","Haemophilia Foundation Australia [Internet]. 2024 [cited 2024 Aug 17]. Fast facts. Available from: https://www.haemophilia.org.au/bleeding-disorders/faqs/fast-facts/","Berntorp E, Fischer K, Hart DP, Mancuso ME, Stephensen D, Shapiro AD, et al. Haemophilia. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2021 Jun 24;7(1):1\u201319."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36055"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2525"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20957"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20957"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tSgOcZPxCM2Q0CKFjUB3PVXxo3c5a5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tSgOcZPxCM2Q0CKFjUB3PVXxo3c5a5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":938}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36055"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-17T20:23:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-17T20:23:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2525"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50814"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haema